ion: Management and Innovation at Leading Design Organizations and Idea Labs -- t22 (Re)design in Management -- t23 Drivers Versus Designers as an Organization’s Building Philosophy -- t24 Managing Change, by Design -- t25 Design Thinking: The Role of Hypotheses Generation and Testing -- t26 The Role of Constraints -- t27 On the Design of Creative Collaboration -- t28 Designing the Australian Tax System -- t29 Persuasive Artifacts -- t30 Designing of What? What Is the Design Stuff Made of? -- tIV Envisioning the future -- t31 The Less, the Better, Perhaps: Learning from Music Language -- t32 Purposes in Lieu of Goals, Enterprises in Lieu of Things -- t33 Designing Learning -- t34 The Managing as Designing Project Calls for a Redesign of the Research Setting! -- t35 Design and Designability -- t36 Public Policy as a Form of Design -- t37 Toward a Design Vocabulary for Management -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aManaging as Designing explores "the design attitude," a new focus for analysis and decision making for managers that draws on examples of decision making and leadership in architecture, art, and design. Based on a series of conference papers given at the opening of the Peter B. Lewis Building (designed by Frank Gehry) at the Weatherhead School of Management, Case Western Reserve University, the book includes keynote speeches from Frank Gehry and Karl Weick. The premise of this book is that managers should act not only as decision makers, but also as designers. Though decision and design are inextricably linked in management action, managers and scholars have too long emphasized the decision face of management over the design face. In a series of essays from a multitude of disciplines, the authors develop a theory of the design attitude in contrast to the more traditionally accepted and practiced decision attitude. The book will appeal primarily to scholars of management theory and organization strategy and managers, with many contributions from a variety of academic backgrounds including architecture, sociology, design, history, choreography, strategy, economics, music, and accounting. There is a potential for strong crossover appeal to these groups, especially to those people and groups interested in design and product development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aBusiness -- Management and Leadership. 4aBusiness -- Organizations and Management Theory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Management.2bisacsh1 aBoland Jr., Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoland, Richard J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBradbury, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchanan, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlsson, Bo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChung, Po, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollopy, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollopy, Fred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCook, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoughlan, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzarniawska, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDechow, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEickmann, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngeström, Yrjö, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaust, Jurgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Ke